NVIDIA Corp. (NVDA.O) Price Target

Guidance for \(\) 54\(bn ex China compares to our\) \ \(52.5bn\) ex China, and buy side expectations of \(\) 54- 55bn\(including\) \ \(3bn+China\) - clear upside excluding the China variable. The bar continues to be high but the growth acceleration is clear.
JulyQ revenue \(\) 1.7bn\(above guidance. Oct guidance\) \ \(54bn\) vs cons \(\) 53.4bn\(, with possible\) \ \(2.5bn\) plus from H20
Expectations were high coming in, but most important boxes were checked. Revenue/EPS growth accelerating ex China, with 2026 outlook more than favorable
At \(\) 175\(stock now at 26.5x our new FY27 non - gaap EPS, and 0.6x PEG (remaining mag 7 average is 2.9x). Making valuation attractive as Blackwell continues to ramp
Remains most preferred in large cap Al, PT to \(\) 210\$

Sentiment has shifted to become much more positive, yet the company still cleared the bar. Just a few weeks ago consensus was \(\) 50\(bn and there were fears of digestion, and now coming into the print consensus had risen to\) \ \(53\) bn including some China (which did not materialize in guidance). That guidance for \(\) 7\(bn of incremental revenue - the first time that a company has guided for that dollar sequential growth - without China. That's in just one quarter, and based on the commentary we heard from management on the call - and what we continue to hear from out checks - continues to represent undershipment of true demand. The continued strength in Hopper is a testament to that, as compute shortages remain intense enough customers are still buying three year old Hoppers to serve some of that demand.

But much of that is appreciated by investors when it comes to the quarter, as we share in our preview. Direct reads to supply chain data points and expectations for China contribution created a somewhat higher bar ahead of tonight's results. But even including the low end of the \(\) 2.5bn\(of potential H20 shipments on the call could have brought guidance to\) \ \(56bn\) , a slightly better headline number of \(60\%\) y/y growth but not really that different fundamentally.
China remains impossible to forecast, and management seemed cautious about prospects to resolve the issues; we continue to leave it out of our numbers
MORGAN STANLEY & CO.LLC
Joseph Moore Equity Analyst
NVIDIA Corp. (NVDA.O, NVDA US)
Shr price, close (Aug 27, 2025)

barring resolution of geopolitical issues. We previewed that China would remain out of forecasts for October; it's clear that even after some licenses have been issued by the US GOV there remain uncertainties (15% US GOV fee, Chinese government product acceptance) that will continue to keep that product from shipping without a resolution. This was at one point 20% of datacenter for Nvidia and while it remains a large market, we simply don't know how large it will be when it comes back, or if it comes back at all.

What do we make of networking strength? Networking can be a lumpy segment, and was flat over the 4 quarter period of FY25 before sharp growth so far this year, with Q1 up \(64\%\) q/q followed by the \(46\%\) we saw today. That has created a networking to GPU revenue ratio that is coming in higher than we would have expected, and probably means that some of those products are leading the way on deliveries vs complete systems. We expect at least some level of normalization in Q3. But it's clear that there's good execution playing a role here as well, with infiband and spectrum both strong.

Nvidia has a tendency to rerate quickly when there is a wall of worry to climb; we don't have that today. But a steady diet of beat and raise quarters should be enough for the stock to work at \(\sim 27x\) EPS. We don't see a clear bear case emerging here, gross margins are steadily improving on their way to mid 70s%, revenue growth is accelerating with the bulk of the Blackwell ramp still in front of us, Rubin is on track, and by all accounts demand for AI compute continues to grow. It's easier to make the case for upside when there is a fundamental overhang on the stock, but even without one the financial profile of mid 50s+ % y/y growth in revenue with \(>60\%\) operating margins will remain attractive as long as beats and raises continue - where our confidence remains high.

Details on the quarter: July revenue of \(46.743bn\) (up \(6.1\%\) q/q and \(55.6\%\) y/y) slightly above the street at \(46.049bn\) and in- line with our estimate of \(46.671bn\) . By segment, Data Center revenue of \(41.096bn\) was up \(5.1\%\) q/q and \(56.4\%\) y/y, Gaming was up \(13.9\%\) q/q and \(48.9\%\) y/y to \(54.287bn\) , Professional Visualization was up \(18.1\%\) q/q and \(32.4\%\) y/y to \(601mn\) , Automotive was up \(3.4\%\) q/q and \(69.4\%\) y/y to \(5586mn\) , and OEM & Other was up \(55.9\%\) q/q and \(96.6\%\) y/y to \(1173mn\) . Gross margin of \(72.7\%\) was slightly above the Street and our estimate of \(72.2\%\) and \(72.3\%\) , respectively. Non- GAAP EPS of \(1.05\) beat both the Street and our estimate of \(1.01\) and \(1.03\) , respectively.

NVIDIA guided for a \(7.3bn\) sequential revenue increase; to \(54bn\) at the midpoint for October (up \(15.5\%\) q/q and \(53.9\%\) y/y), which came in ahead of the Street and our estimate of \(53.433bn\) and \(52.567bn\) , respectively, with data center once again the biggest contributor to growth. The company guided gross margin to \(73.5\%\) , compared to the Street at \(72.8\%\) and our estimate of \(73.1\%\) .

Raising estimates: We are increasing our revenue estimates for FY26 (CY25), but maintain roughly \(34\%\) y/y growth in FY27 and \(16\%\) growth in FY28. For the October quarter we move revenue from \(52.567bn\) to \(54.420bn\) and non- GAAP EPS from \(1.20\) to \(1.25\) . For FY26 our revenue and non- GAAP EPS move from \(203.368bn\) / \(4.45\) to \(206.448/4.54\) , and FY27 comes up to \(278.035bn/6.59\) from \(273.228bn/6.51\) previously.

Thoughts on the stock: For the stock to sell off slightly after holding on these types of numbers certainly indicates that sentiment has largely caught up to the growth potential, after fears of digestion just a few weeks ago. But outside of China geopolitics, this is a very clean beat and raise quarter. Product roadmaps are on time, gross margins are tracking, outperforming vs. ASICs in CY25 is notable (though we expect some mean reversion in CY26).

Through this strong AI cycle, we have been consistently positive on NVIDIA, but our enthusiasm is highest when there are short term concerns that we think can be disproved; that isn't the case now, as investor enthusiasm remains quite high for all of CY26. That said, on peak earnings power we still see the stock as less expensive than other AI beneficiaries, while everything else in semis continues to suffer from cyclical pressures. So from here the upside to our PT has come down given the appreciation in the stock, but we continue to see this as the best risk reward in the AI space.

In terms of our PT we maintain our prior methodology of 33x MW eps sets for CY26. On our new \(6.36\) MW EPS that brings the PT up to \(210\) vs \(200 previously. 33x MW represents about 32x our new non- GAAP estimate of\) 6.59. And a discount to large cap AI semis peer AVGO.
